snippet.textDisplay: My mum lost her dad to kidney cancer. He was diagnosed when I was only 6 months old. My grandad meant the world to my mum, nanny and uncle. My dad was abused when he was younger and my grandad helped him mature into a man and helped him get a job. There was nothing my grandad would not have done for his family. He was a great man from what I heard and every day we still think of him. He was so happy to live the way he did and see everything he wanted. I will be donating to love from Sean, as well as Macmillan cancer support as they helped my grandad and my family through everything. I never got to know him, but it feels like he’s still here helping us through the worse! You’ve done an amazing documentary and helped many people, just like your father would have done. ❤️❤️

snippet.textDisplay: This is the hardest comment I've ever had to make. How do I do this without typing a book? It took me 3 sessions to complete this Tribute Doc. I'm simply going to say I am SO proud of the two of you for delving deep and making this. I am Blessed and inspired by a man that I will never meet and I am thankful to two powerfully influenced young men to share their journey of healing and new found purpose to help others that THEY may never meet. You cannot help but make your father Proud. Now LIVE and find your joy and show your dad how high he taught you to soar.

snippet.textDisplay: 3 weeks ago I lost my father to cancer. This video could not have come at better time where I needed someone to relate to, cry with, to feel helpless and hopeful all at the sometime with. All I can say to these 2 brave men is thank you... Thank you for making this video and allowing me to go through my grieving process with you. All of these emotions are very raw and very real and its the exact emotions I have felt through the 2 year battle with my father. Sean and my father have a very similar story. My dad was given months and braved the battled with strength and positivity for 2 years. He was a kind, selfless, loving soul much like Sean. He made an impact on not just his family but everyone he came in contact with. Through his journey I've felt broken, angry, and left questioning why bad things happen to good people. People that care so much for others and make this world a better place. My dad faced his battle with bravery much like Sean. He carried hope and humour every day even as his body slowly gave up on him. He loved his wife and children so deeply he never gave up and never showed fear simply to keep us in the best spirit possible. Cancer is an ugly and devastating creature that has torn many families apart and forced too many early goodbyes. As a victim of cancer related tragedy thank you all for donating. This is a battle that takes a community to survive and overcome.

snippet.textDisplay: When I heard Ethan say "maybe passing away is the best option" I traveled back in time when my grandpa died from cancer. He was one of my bestfriends and I didn't want him to go, but I wanted his sickness and pain to end. Losing my grandpa doesn't compare to these two, the people I look up to the most, losing their father. They lost their bestfriend and I don't know if I would be able to be as strong as everybody shown in this video if I lost my bestfriend. Sean is so proud of you two and Cameron and Lisa and everybody he was related to/friends with and he is looking down on all of us smiling from ear to ear. I love you guys and stay strong!

snippet.textDisplay: Dear Dolan Twins, you love your dad so much and crying over his loss is not a bad thing, he wants you to cry because losing someone is so difficult and crying is something that everyone does. snippet.textDisplay: This is the most touching film i’ve ever watched. Personally I’ve thankfully never had to endure the loss of a parent or loved one, but I still cried along with you guys and felt the emotions pouring through the screen. snippet.textDisplay: 30-something-year-old mom here. Not sure if Ethan and Grayson read comments, I hope you do so you can feel the outpouring of L O V E all these people have for you and your family. My teenage son enjoys your videos and being a mom I had to see for myself what you were about... and I love what I see from 2015 all the way to 2020. Your encouragement for young people to be themselves and not worry about "fitting in" is gold and a valuable message to send. My heart hurts for your family's loss. Thank you for allowing us to see your hearts and helping us find more ways to fight cancer and all the pain left in its wake. Wishing you health, healing, and much love💕
